  "prompt": "How are polar covalent bonds formed?",
  "response": "Polar covalent bonds are formed when two atoms share electrons, but the electrons are not shared equally due to a difference in electronegativity between the atoms. Here's a step-by-step explanation of how they form:\n\n1. **Electronegativity Difference**: Electronegativity is the ability of an atom to attract shared electrons in a chemical bond. When two atoms with different electronegativities form a covalent bond, the more electronegative atom attracts the shared electrons more strongly.\n\n2. **Unequal Sharing of Electrons**: As a result of the difference in electronegativity, the shared electrons spend more time closer to the more electronegative atom than to the less electronegative one. This creates an uneven distribution of electron density in the bond.\n\n3. **Formation of Partial Charges**: The atom with the higher electronegativity gains a slight negative charge (\u03b4-) because it has a greater share of the electron density. Conversely, the atom with the lower electronegativity gains a slight positive charge (\u03b4+) because it has less of the electron density.\n\n4. **Creation of a Dipole**: The separation of charges results in the formation of a dipole, which is a molecule or part of a molecule that has a positive end and a negative end. This dipole moment is characteristic of polar covalent bonds.\n\nA classic example of a polar covalent bond is the bond between hydrogen and oxygen in water (H\u2082O). Oxygen, being more electronegative than hydrogen, attracts the shared electrons more strongly, resulting in a polar bond. The polarity of these bonds gives water many of its unique properties, such as its high surface tension, specific heat capacity, and ability to dissolve many substances.",
